[{'text': 'After you have unpacked and assembled your bike, position the Shapeshifter remote so you have easy access to the gear levers.', 'start': 12.133, 'duration': 8.7}, {'text': 'Activate XC Mode to set up Shapeshifter. All you have to do is push the remote.', 'start': 21.84, 'duration': 4.0}, {'text': 'You can tell Shapeshifter is in XC Mode when the indicator at the top of the linkage shows green.', 'start': 26.5, 'duration': 2.98}, {'text': 'You will have received a shock pump with this special adapter when your bike was delivered.', 'start': 31.04, 'duration': 2.26}, {'text': 'Screw the adapter onto the end of the shock pump.', 'start': 35.84, 'duration': 1.96}, {'text': 'Then turn the black dial above. The air pressure in the system should now be shown on your shock pump pressure gauge.', 'start': 38.5, 'duration': 2.74}, {'text': 'Remove the dust cap on top of the rocker arm and screw on the shock pump by turning the silver dial.', 'start': 41.66, 'duration': 10.24}, {'text': 'Now pump up to the recommended pressure according to the values shown in the table.', 'start': 53.2, 'duration': 3.3}, {'text': 'The first time you connect the shock pump the pressure gauge should read between 9-11 bar.', 'start': 57.02, 'duration': 4.66}, {'text': 'Once the correct pressure has been set, unscrew the black dial to close the valve.', 'start': 62.78, 'duration': 1.82}, {'text': 'Before unscrewing the shock pump entirely you should release any air left in the tube by pressing the button at the side of the pressure gauge. ', 'start': 69.42, 'duration': 8.62}, {'text': 'This will make the pump easier to remove.', 'start': 79.38, 'duration': 2.2}, {'text': 'Turn the silver dial to remove the pump.', 'start': 82.66, 'duration': 3.18}, {'text': 'Don’t forget to replace the dust cap on top of the rocker arm.', 'start': 86.62, 'duration': 3.86}, {'text': 'If you connect the pump for a second time, air escapes into the tube meaning the pressure gauge will give off a reading about 5 bar lower than before.', 'start': 91.98, 'duration': 5.62}, {'text': 'You therefore have to pump the gas spring up again to the required pressure. ', 'start': 98.06, 'duration': 2.0}, {'text': 'Now you can set suspension sag.', 'start': 101.4, 'duration': 2.06}, {'text': 'Put the bike into DH Mode first.', 'start': 103.6, 'duration': 1.66}, {'text': 'To do this, push and hold down the Shapeshifter remote and at the same time shift your body weight to the rear and compress the suspension once through your heels. ', 'start': 106.58, 'duration': 7.34}, {'text': 'To shift into DH Mode hold down the remote, stand on the pedals and move your weight to the rear.', 'start': 115.1, 'duration': 8.12}, {'text': 'Release the remote.', 'start': 124.5, 'duration': 2.26}, {'text': 'Once in DH Mode you will notice the bike’s slacker angles and plusher suspension feel.', 'start': 127.78, 'duration': 4.26}, {'text': 'If you cannot easily shift to DH Mode, then reduce the air pressure in the rear shock.', 'start': 133.08, 'duration': 4.64}, {'text': 'Then sit on the bike with your full weight and use the o-ring to check suspension sag.', 'start': 139.1, 'duration': 4.28}, {'text': 'This should be 25% of full travel.', 'start': 144.1, 'duration': 2.38}, {'text': 'If you have too much sag, pump more air into the shock and check again. ', 'start': 146.8, 'duration': 2.92}, {'text': 'If there is not enough sag, then use the button on the pump to release air from the shock. ', 'start': 150.72, 'duration': 4.88}, {'text': 'Repeat this process until you hit 25% sag, that way Shapeshifter and the rear shock can work best together.', 'start': 156.34, 'duration': 4.78}, {'text': 'Now you’re ready to ride. ', 'start': 161.56, 'duration': 3.44}, {'text': 'To shift back to XC Mode simply hold down the remote, stand on the pedals, raise your heels and unweight the rear wheel.', 'start': 167.1, 'duration': 13.9}, {'text': 'This unloads the system allowing the gas spring to decompress.', 'start': 182.1, 'duration': 3.06}, {'text': 'Release the remote before returning to a central riding position.', 'start': 186.7, 'duration': 5.34}, {'text': 'XC Mode gives you steeper angles and a firmer suspension feel for extra efficiency.', 'start': 193.2, 'duration': 5.5}]

and BodyTransformationTruth.com, and in this', 'start': 6.04, 'duration': 4.952}, {'text': 'video I want to share with you my top 3 recommended
posterior deltoid exercises, or “rear delts”', 'start': 10.992, 'duration': 6.278}, {'text': 'for short, which is of course the rear head
of the shoulder.', 'start': 17.27, 'duration': 2.57}, {'text': 'Now I did do a video on this something like
2 years ago but I didn’t include actual', 'start': 19.84, 'duration': 5.04}, {'text': 'live demonstrations of the exercises and so
I just wanted to update this with a higher', 'start': 24.88, 'duration': 4.67}, {'text': 'quality version and showing you 3 exercises
instead of only 2.', 'start': 29.55, 'duration': 4.61}, {'text': 'Now just really quickly before I show you
the exercises, I do recommend that everybody', 'start': 34.16, 'duration': 5.07}, {'text': 'out there include at least some direct rear
delt training in their plan for the simple', 'start': 39.23, 'duration': 5.27}, {'text': 'reason that it’s usually a neglected muscle
and most lifters out there do have an imbalance', 'start': 44.5, 'duration': 5.52}, {'text': 'in that their front delts and their pecs are
more developed in comparison to their upper', 'start': 50.02, 'duration': 4.94}, {'text': 'back and rear delts, which makes your upper
body look disproportionate and it also creates', 'start': 54.96, 'duration': 5.71}, {'text': 'instability in your shoulder joint which can
easily lead to injuries over the long term.', 'start': 60.67, 'duration': 4.73}, {'text': 'So, there are a lot of different rear deltoid
exercises out there to choose from but these', 'start': 65.4, 'duration': 5.84}, {'text': 'would be my top 3 picks.', 'start': 71.24, 'duration': 2.4}, {'text': 'So posterior deltoid exercise #1 are face
pulls.', 'start': 73.64, 'duration': 3.07}, {'text': 'Now I’ve covered these before, they are
a pretty uncommon lift but I pretty much include', 'start': 76.71, 'duration': 4.46}, {'text': 'face pulls as a staple in my own routines
and in the routines that I give to other people', 'start': 81.17, 'duration': 4.93}, {'text': 'because they not only train your rear delts
effectively but they also hit your traps,', 'start': 86.1, 'duration': 5.82}, {'text': 'rhomboids, the other smaller muscles of your
upper back, as well as your rotator cuffs,', 'start': 91.92, 'duration': 5.129}, {'text': "and that's going to help youcounteract that
upper body imbalance that I just mentioned.", 'start': 97.049, 'duration': 4.0}, {'text': 'So to perform these, set a cable at upper
chest height using a rope attachment.', 'start': 101.049, 'duration': 4.771}, {'text': 'Grab onto the ends of the rope from underneath
using a neutral hammer style grip.', 'start': 105.82, 'duration': 5.86}, {'text': 'Most people perform their face pulls by gripping
the rope from the top with the palms facing', 'start': 111.68, 'duration': 4.86}, {'text': "down, and that's still effective but the variation
that I outline here is going to give you a", 'start': 116.54, 'duration': 4.73}, {'text': 'larger range of motion and more external rotation
of your shoulders as you pull the rope backward.', 'start': 121.27, 'duration': 6.459}, {'text': 'So with your chest up, with your shoulders
down and back, your scapula retracted and', 'start': 127.729, 'duration': 5.861}, {'text': 'your head stationary, pull the rope towards
your face while at the same time imagining', 'start': 133.59, 'duration': 5.409}, {'text': 'that you’re trying to pull the rope apart,
and a good form cue here is to imagine that', 'start': 138.999, 'duration': 4.89}, {'text': 'you were hitting a back double bicep pose
on each rep.', 'start': 143.889, 'duration': 3.791}, {'text': 'Squeeze your rear delts and your upper back,
and then return back to the starting position.', 'start': 147.68, 'duration': 5.43}, {'text': 'Posterior deltoid exercise #2 are Bent Over
Rear Lateral Cable Raises.', 'start': 153.11, 'duration': 4.83}, {'text': 'Now this one is a direct isolation exercise
for the rear delts, it can be done using dumbbells', 'start': 157.94, 'duration': 5.64}, {'text': 'also, but I would suggest going with the cable
variation if you can because dumbbells really', 'start': 163.58, 'duration': 5.67}, {'text': "don't give you a significant amount of resistance
in the bottom half of the exercise and they", 'start': 169.25, 'duration': 4.95}, {'text': 'only really hit your rear delts toward the
middle and top half of the range of motion.', 'start': 174.2, 'duration': 4.939}, {'text': "Either variation is still going to be effective,
but if you do have cables available then you'll", 'start': 179.139, 'duration': 4.55}, {'text': 'definitely feel the difference by using that
version.', 'start': 183.689, 'duration': 2.88}, {'text': 'So just start off in a bent over position
with your upper body just above parallel to', 'start': 186.569, 'duration': 4.48}, {'text': 'the ground.', 'start': 191.049, 'duration': 1.231}, {'text': 'Grab onto the cable using a single-hand attachment
with a neutral grip.', 'start': 192.28, 'duration': 4.969}, {'text': 'From there, allow your shoulder to hang forward
slightly and keep your scapula flat rather', 'start': 197.249, 'duration': 6.32}, {'text': 'than retracted.', 'start': 203.569, 'duration': 1.361}, {'text': 'Keeping your shoulder in that sort of "hanging
forward" position and your upper back flat,', 'start': 204.93, 'duration': 5.44}, {'text': "that's going to direct more of the tension
onto your rear delt, there's nothing wrong", 'start': 210.37, 'duration': 3.929}, {'text': 'with involving the muscles of your upper back
here, but with this particular exercise we', 'start': 214.299, 'duration': 5.36}, {'text': 'want to focus on pure rear delt isolation.', 'start': 219.659, 'duration': 2.65}, {'text': 'So, after that, just raise the cable out to
your side until you feel a strong contraction', 'start': 222.309, 'duration': 4.731}, {'text': 'in the rear delt, and make sure to focus on
pulling through your elbow rather than your', 'start': 227.04, 'duration': 4.679}, {'text': 'hand and really make sure to emphasize control
on this one rather than just heaving the weight', 'start': 231.719, 'duration': 5.47}, {'text': 'up from point A to B. You can also do this
exercise from a standing position in between', 'start': 237.189, 'duration': 5.44}, {'text': 'a cable stand like you see here, or you can
also experiment by performing it using a reverse', 'start': 242.629, 'duration': 7.26}, {'text': 'pec deck machine if you have one available.', 'start': 249.889, 'duration': 2.69}, {'text': 'And posterior deltoid exercise #3 are rear
delt dumbbell rows.', 'start': 252.579, 'duration': 4.211}, {'text': 'So this one I’d consider as an optional
add-on if you justwant to throw in some more', 'start': 256.79, 'duration': 4.43}, {'text': 'volume or if you want to try a new exercise.', 'start': 261.22, 'duration': 2.94}, {'text': 'This is pretty similar to a one arm dumbbell
row that you would perform for your lats except', 'start': 264.16, 'duration': 4.71}, {'text': 'that instead of tucking your arm in toward
your side, you actually want to flare it outward', 'start': 268.87, 'duration': 5.02}, {'text': 'so that your upper arm is perpendicular to
your body, and on top of that you also want', 'start': 273.89, 'duration': 5.3}, {'text': 'to keep your upper body basically parallel
to the floor or just slightly higher.', 'start': 279.19, 'duration': 4.93}, {'text': 'So from that position just row the dumbbell
up toward your chest while focusing on squeezing', 'start': 284.12, 'duration': 5.49}, {'text': 'your rear delt in the process.', 'start': 289.61, 'duration': 2.05}, {'text': 'I do prefer the one arm dumbbell variation
here because it keeps your lower back supported', 'start': 291.66, 'duration': 4.97}, {'text': 'and it also lets you work each arm independently,
but rear delt rows can also be done in a standing', 'start': 296.63, 'duration': 6.09}, {'text': 'position using a barbell or just using two
dumbbells.', 'start': 302.72, 'duration': 3.85}, {'text': 'Or, if you have a machine row available that
lets you perform the exercise with your upper', 'start': 306.57, 'duration': 5.5}, {'text': 'arms perpendicular to your body and where
you can row the weight up to your chest, then', 'start': 312.07, 'duration': 4.15}, {'text': 'that’s also an acceptable option as well.', 'start': 316.22, 'duration': 2.81}, {'text': 'So my recommendation is to hit your rear delts
directly 1-2 times per week, performing 3', 'start': 319.03, 'duration': 4.88}, {'text': 'sets per exercise, and again you can either
